SALTING EXAMPLE
salting is used to fix skewed join. For example if one customer id have more than 100 GB data in order table
df=spark.range(4).alias("salt_key")
customer = spark.table("customer").crossJoin(df)
orders = spark.table("orders").withColumn("salt_key", (F.rand() * 4).cast("int").alias("salt_key"))
out = customer.join(orders, (orders.customer_id = customers.customer_id) & (customer.salt_key = order.salt_key), "inner")

AQE can internally optimize skewed join. Following properties need to be enabled for skewed join issue in spark
Below property is set by default false by spark to avoid shuffling
spark.sql.adaptive.forceOptimizeSkewedJoin = true  (adaptive rule to optimize skewed joins to avoid straggler tasks, even if it introduces extra shuffle.)
Below parameter need to adjusted to avoid creating very small partition of shuffled data.
spark.sql.adaptive.skewJoin.skewedPartitionThresholdInBytes = 256MB (A partition is considered as skewed if its size in bytes is larger than this threshold)
spark.sql.adaptive.skewJoin.skewedPartitionFactor = 5 (A partition is considered as skewed if its size is larger than this factor multiplying the median partition size)

By default spark does broadcast join if table size is 10MB. In Real life scenario. Most of tables are larger 10MB
below properties need to be changed to improve broadcast join performance
spark.sql.autoBroadcastJoinThreshold = 1 GB
Larger table broadcast takes time. so timeout need to increased for larger table
spark.sql.broadcastTimeout = 15000
Below property need to be changed for large data shuffling
It configures the number of partitions to use when shuffling data for joins or aggregations.
spark.sql.shuffle.partitions = 500

Cache is another optimization technique, Cache must of done if dataframe is reused multiple time
Cache utilization ratio in spark ui is used to validate the cache is utilized or not.
Below is right use of cache
df = spark.table("employee")
df.filter("employee_id = 1")
df.filter("employee_id = 2")
Below are issue faced if cache is done at wrong place.
1. disk spilling
2. Cache takes cpu time of serialzation and deserialzation
Below are steps need to be followed to ensure cache is right or not
1. check that dataframe or table is used mutliple time
2. ensure that there is some extra memory exist for cache
3. check for spark that cache utilization ratio is better

